      <h1 class="sc-title">The Score That Actually Matters</h1>

      <div class="sc-body">

        <p>The art world has a scoring system. Price. Placement. Which galleries, which collectors, which critics bother to show up. Win those metrics and you're in the game. Ignore them and you're not.</p>

        <p>Thomas Hobbes saw this coming — not about art specifically, but about power in general. He wrote in the 17th century that real power wasn't strength or military force. It was the ability to define the terms of success. Whoever names the game controls who wins it.</p>

        <p>Four hundred years later, philosopher C. Thi Nguyen put a sharper point on it. He calls it value capture: the moment when an external scoring system stops just evaluating you and starts reshaping what you actually want. You stop asking whether the work holds people. You start asking whether it scores. The insight is the same one Hobbes had. Nguyen just has the neuroscience to explain why it's so hard to resist.</p>

        <p>The art world has been running this play the whole time.</p>

        <hr class="sc-rule">

        <p>I've been thinking about a different score. One that measures what I think we're actually trying to do.</p>

        <p>When I'm in the studio, the thing I keep coming back to isn't price or placement. It's a simpler question: will someone stand in front of this long enough for something to happen to them?</p>

        <p>I call it dwell time — how long a work holds someone before they move on. It sounds almost too simple. But the more I've looked at what separates work that lands from work that doesn't, across a lot of different kinds of work and a lot of different viewers, the more it keeps coming back to this. The work either holds the body in place or it doesn't.</p>

        <p>And that's not random. It's not taste. It's not about whether the viewer is educated or sophisticated or the right kind of person. It's about specific formal decisions made in the studio — decisions that operate on the viewer's nervous system before their brain has a chance to weigh in.</p>

        <hr class="sc-rule">

        <p>Matthew Pelowski studied what happened to visitors at the Rothko Chapel. Not what they thought about the paintings. What happened to them physically when they stayed long enough in front of those paintings. Some of them cried. Not because they'd read the catalog essay. Because the work held them there past the point where their body could stay neutral.</p>

        <p>That's the thing I keep returning to. The crying isn't the point. The mechanism is. Something in the work kept them there long enough for a pre-verbal response to surface — before interpretation, before judgment, before the viewer decided whether they were the kind of person who understands art. The nervous system just reported in.</p>

        <p>Rothko understood this at the level of formal decision-making. Those 15-foot canvases weren't a stylistic choice. A painting that fills your peripheral vision stops being something you look at. You're inside it. Scale activates a different perceptual response than a canvas you can take in from across the room. He was working the mechanism deliberately.</p>

        <hr class="sc-rule">

        <p>I've spent years trying to understand, then map, what those mechanisms actually are. The framework behind Art Lab — 54 principles drawn from neuroaesthetics research, perceptual psychology, and studio practice — describes how visual communication works underneath style, underneath content, underneath intention. Before meaning has a chance to arrive.</p>

        <p>Some of these principles fire almost universally, across cultures, training levels, viewers who've never been in a museum. Face detection. Figure-ground relationships. Edge and contrast. Light source logic. These aren't aesthetic preferences. They're how the visual system operates.</p>

        <p>Others are more contingent — shaped by cultural conditioning or art training. Real, but less universal.</p>

        <p>What I keep noticing in my own work, and in work I'm looking at closely, is that dwell time lives or dies in the gap between intention and mechanism. An accidental hard edge in a corner. A configuration of shapes that reads as a face when you didn't plan one. Contradictory shadow directions that make the space feel wrong without the viewer knowing why. These things bleed attention, quietly, invisibly. The viewer moves on and can't tell you why.</p>

        <p>When you know what the mechanisms are, you know what you're trading. You can make the violation intentional instead of accidental. That's a different kind of control than the art market gives you — but it's real, and it's yours.</p>

        <hr class="sc-rule">

        <p>Here's the thing I want to be careful about: the art world isn't always wrong.</p>

        <p>Sometimes the market lands on the right work. Sometimes the critical apparatus recognizes something real — a painting that actually holds, that actually does something to the body before the brain intercepts it. The scoring system is unfair and often distorted, but it isn't purely arbitrary. Authenticity does get awarded. Just inconsistently, and for reasons nobody in the room can usually articulate.</p>

        <p>What Art Lab gives you isn't a way around that system. It's closer to a way of understanding what the system is sometimes actually responding to. When a work holds, when dwell time is high, there are formal reasons. Specific decisions that created specific conditions. Knowing those reasons doesn't make the work less authentic. It makes the authenticity more available. You stop depending on instinct alone. You know what you're doing and why it's working — which means you can do it on purpose, keep doing it, and push further into it.</p>

        <p>That's not the opposite of authentic. That's what craft actually is.</p>

        <hr class="sc-rule">

        <p>The art world will keep scoring what it scores. I'm not pretending the market doesn't exist.</p>

        <p>But there's a score that's been there the whole time, running underneath all of it. How long someone stands there. Whether their body stays in front of the work past the point of politeness. Whether something happens to them before they've decided how to feel about it.</p>

        <p>Hobbes named the problem four centuries ago. Nguyen sharpened it last year. The art world is still running the same play.</p>

        <p>I'm interested in a different game.</p>

      </div>

